WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.430 --> 00:00:03.940
BILL DUANE: Good
morning everyone.

00:00:03.940 --> 00:00:06.670
Super happy to see you all.

00:00:06.670 --> 00:00:08.380
My name is Bill
Duane, and I look

00:00:08.380 --> 00:00:12.390
after the well-being learning
programs here at Google.

00:00:12.390 --> 00:00:19.140
And we're here today to speak
with a friend and partner, Andy

00:00:19.140 --> 00:00:21.980
Puddicombe, from Headspace.

00:00:21.980 --> 00:00:29.660
And the intention of today is to
mostly practice, and to try out

00:00:29.660 --> 00:00:33.240
a number of different
styles of meditation.

00:00:33.240 --> 00:00:36.110
And also to talk a little
bit about meditation itself.

00:00:36.110 --> 00:00:38.680
But for the most part,
to actually get our hands

00:00:38.680 --> 00:00:41.670
dirty, and get
into the practice.

00:00:41.670 --> 00:00:46.890
So I'd like to start
off by introducing Andy.

00:00:46.890 --> 00:00:48.620
Andy is the founder
of Headspace,

00:00:48.620 --> 00:00:50.600
which is a mindfulness
app that we

00:00:50.600 --> 00:00:55.710
use in conjunction with our
in-person sits, and detachment

00:00:55.710 --> 00:00:59.890
days and a number of
other meditation programs.

00:00:59.890 --> 00:01:01.810
And it's really been
remarkable, it's

00:01:01.810 --> 00:01:04.010
been remarkable to get to
know Andy and his team.

00:01:04.010 --> 00:01:07.190
And also to get the benefits
of the Headspace app, which

00:01:07.190 --> 00:01:09.970
probably some of you guys
have also checked out also.

00:01:09.970 --> 00:01:13.639
So in some ways, Andy
could be a Googler, right?

00:01:13.639 --> 00:01:15.930
There's a lot of people here
with interesting and weird

00:01:15.930 --> 00:01:18.640
backgrounds.

00:01:18.640 --> 00:01:22.380
I'm looking at my friend,
Mario, who teaches SAY,

00:01:22.380 --> 00:01:25.840
and on the side is a medical
doctor and has a Ph.D.

00:01:25.840 --> 00:01:28.510
In neuroscience.

00:01:28.510 --> 00:01:33.020
There's many other stories
like that in the audience.

00:01:33.020 --> 00:01:34.540
And Andy was a monk.

00:01:34.540 --> 00:01:36.600
You know, normally
it's like a technology

00:01:36.600 --> 00:01:38.420
founder, monastic background.

00:01:38.420 --> 00:01:40.670
ANDY PUDDICOMBE: There are
a few clues, though, right?

00:01:43.590 --> 00:01:45.969
BILL DUANE: So how long
were you a monk for?

00:01:45.969 --> 00:01:48.010
ANDY PUDDICOMBE: So I
trained for about 10 years.

00:01:48.010 --> 00:01:52.390
First in the Burmese tradition,
and then for about five years

00:01:52.390 --> 00:01:53.644
in the Tibetan tradition.

00:01:53.644 --> 00:01:55.060
So I trained first
as a layperson,

00:01:55.060 --> 00:01:58.030
then as a novice monk, and
then as a fully ordained monk

00:01:58.030 --> 00:02:00.520
in the Tibetan tradition.

00:02:00.520 --> 00:02:03.150
BILL DUANE: And then what
drew you into the position

00:02:03.150 --> 00:02:04.610
that you're in now?

00:02:04.610 --> 00:02:09.150
ANDY PUDDICOMBE: Yes, so
I'd finished my training

00:02:09.150 --> 00:02:10.180
at the monastery.

00:02:10.180 --> 00:02:12.930
You never really finish it, but
I finished a period of training

00:02:12.930 --> 00:02:13.840
at the monastery.

00:02:13.840 --> 00:02:18.300
And I'd been sent
away to go and teach

00:02:18.300 --> 00:02:21.230
meditation in the
Meditation Center in Moscow,

00:02:21.230 --> 00:02:23.640
of all places.

00:02:23.640 --> 00:02:27.010
It was as far away as
they could send me.

00:02:27.010 --> 00:02:29.910
And I was there and
a lot of ex-pats

00:02:29.910 --> 00:02:33.090
used to come along to
the Meditation Center.

00:02:33.090 --> 00:02:34.660
And there was one
in particular who

00:02:34.660 --> 00:02:38.610
was really keen for me to go
in and work with his staff.

00:02:38.610 --> 00:02:40.850
And it was in an oil company.

00:02:40.850 --> 00:02:42.730
Again this is in Moscow.

00:02:42.730 --> 00:02:46.850
And he d I'd love to have you
in, but dressed like that?

00:02:46.850 --> 00:02:50.040
So I was in my robes, and
for all intents and purposes,

00:02:50.040 --> 00:02:51.970
for anyone not familiar
with Tibetan Buddhism,

00:02:51.970 --> 00:02:54.236
I was basically a
bald guy in a skirt.

00:02:54.236 --> 00:02:56.360
So he's all, we're never
going to get you in there,

00:02:56.360 --> 00:02:57.109
dressed like that.

00:02:57.109 --> 00:02:58.895
And it got me
thinking, you know?

00:02:58.895 --> 00:02:59.890
What do I care about?

00:02:59.890 --> 00:03:00.750
What am I passionate about?

00:03:00.750 --> 00:03:02.375
Am I passionate about
the being a monk,

00:03:02.375 --> 00:03:04.140
or passionate about
teaching meditation?

00:03:04.140 --> 00:03:06.056
It was a really easy
choice to make, actually.

00:03:06.056 --> 00:03:08.300
So when I spoke to my teacher,
and I finished my time

00:03:08.300 --> 00:03:14.432
as a monk, and I started working
more in that type of space.

00:03:14.432 --> 00:03:15.640
BILL DUANE: Now, I'm curious.

00:03:15.640 --> 00:03:19.770
When did you get the time to do
the voice acting with the Geico

00:03:19.770 --> 00:03:21.130
gecko commercials?

00:03:21.130 --> 00:03:24.220
ANDY PUDDICOMBE: See, I didn't
get this until this morning.

00:03:24.220 --> 00:03:27.570
They actually had to take me
through this, this morning.

00:03:27.570 --> 00:03:28.480
I said, what?

00:03:28.480 --> 00:03:29.945
And even when he
did play it, I was

00:03:29.945 --> 00:03:30.630
like, what, that sounds like me?

00:03:30.630 --> 00:03:31.250
Really?

00:03:31.250 --> 00:03:33.909
BILL DUANE: Wait,
wait, am crazy?

00:03:33.909 --> 00:03:35.950
When I first started
listening the Headspace app,

00:03:35.950 --> 00:03:37.575
I was like, shit,
that guys sounds just

00:03:37.575 --> 00:03:39.375
like the Geico gecko.

00:03:39.375 --> 00:03:40.040
Am I alone?

00:03:40.040 --> 00:03:40.546
Or is there anyone else?

00:03:40.546 --> 00:03:42.212
And I'm sorry if I've
ruined it for you.

00:03:42.212 --> 00:03:45.034
ANDY PUDDICOMBE:
So, I don't know

00:03:45.034 --> 00:03:47.200
if there's an especially
high adoption rate to Geico

00:03:47.200 --> 00:03:49.280
insurance, so I've
been dropping in

00:03:49.280 --> 00:03:52.050
throughout take 10,
take 15, take 20.

00:03:52.050 --> 00:03:53.507
You will buy our-- no.

00:03:53.507 --> 00:03:54.840
BILL DUANE: Subliminal messages.

00:03:54.840 --> 00:03:57.430
That's why the app is so
inexpensive for Googlers.

00:03:57.430 --> 00:03:59.555
It has subliminal messages
to get you to buy Geico.

00:03:59.555 --> 00:04:01.054
ANDY PUDDICOMBE:
Sponsored by Geico.

00:04:01.054 --> 00:04:03.140
BILL DUANE: I thought this
might go off the rails,

00:04:03.140 --> 00:04:05.473
but I wasn't-- I didn't think
it would quite so quickly,

00:04:05.473 --> 00:04:06.460
but fair enough.

00:04:10.200 --> 00:04:13.020
So, practice.

00:04:13.020 --> 00:04:15.490
I was curious who's
in the room, in terms

00:04:15.490 --> 00:04:17.279
of practice experience.

00:04:17.279 --> 00:04:19.512
That will sort of help
us guide and curate

00:04:19.512 --> 00:04:20.470
what we're doing today.

00:04:20.470 --> 00:04:23.720
So who here is brand new?

00:04:23.720 --> 00:04:25.122
OK, awesome, welcome, welcome.

00:04:25.122 --> 00:04:26.830
Thank you for coming
to a tech talk, even

00:04:26.830 --> 00:04:29.310
those who knows what
you thought it might be.

00:04:29.310 --> 00:04:32.100
We'll make sure
that this is geared.

00:04:32.100 --> 00:04:35.239
And how many people
have a daily practice?

00:04:35.239 --> 00:04:36.780
ANDY PUDDICOMBE:
Great, look at that.

00:04:36.780 --> 00:04:38.960
BILL DUANE: How
many people would

00:04:38.960 --> 00:04:41.966
like to have a daily practice,
but aren't quite there yet?

00:04:41.966 --> 00:04:43.090
Thank you for being honest.

00:04:43.090 --> 00:04:44.732
ANDY PUDDICOMBE: There's many.

00:04:44.732 --> 00:04:45.690
BILL DUANE: Super cool.

00:04:45.690 --> 00:04:48.862
All right, I think that gives
us a good cross section.

00:04:48.862 --> 00:04:49.820
ANDY PUDDICOMBE: Great.

00:04:49.820 --> 00:04:54.240
Well, I had a teacher who
always used to say to me,

00:04:54.240 --> 00:04:56.590
unless you can
improve on silence,

00:04:56.590 --> 00:04:59.300
it's better not to
say anything at all.

00:04:59.300 --> 00:05:01.789
And I thought about
that for today.

00:05:01.789 --> 00:05:04.080
And I thought, it probably
wouldn't be that interesting

00:05:04.080 --> 00:05:05.810
if we just sat here
for 90 minutes,

00:05:05.810 --> 00:05:08.334
and really didn't
say anything at all.

00:05:08.334 --> 00:05:10.250
It's an interesting kind
of balance to strike.

00:05:10.250 --> 00:05:12.010
Because we have
to say something.

00:05:12.010 --> 00:05:12.590
Right?

00:05:12.590 --> 00:05:15.560
I think we can't just come
to meditation and just sit.

00:05:15.560 --> 00:05:17.310
For most of us that's
a bit of a struggle.

00:05:17.310 --> 00:05:18.726
And even when we
learn to do that,

00:05:18.726 --> 00:05:22.390
it then becomes a struggle
to do it every day.

00:05:22.390 --> 00:05:24.420
But I do think that
balance is important.

00:05:24.420 --> 00:05:25.952
There's so much
chatter around, I

00:05:25.952 --> 00:05:27.660
don't know how you
feel about this, Bill.

00:05:27.660 --> 00:05:29.243
There's so much
chatter and discussion

00:05:29.243 --> 00:05:30.850
around my mindfulness
at the moment,

00:05:30.850 --> 00:05:34.230
that we're at kind of risk of
creating so much noise in that,

00:05:34.230 --> 00:05:35.790
that we miss out
on the very thing

00:05:35.790 --> 00:05:39.140
that we set out to discover
in the first place.

00:05:39.140 --> 00:05:42.270
It reminded me of a chef.

00:05:42.270 --> 00:05:44.366
When I was much, much
younger working at school I

00:05:44.366 --> 00:05:44.960
used to work in the kitchen.

00:05:44.960 --> 00:05:46.935
And he was really
kind of a hectic chef.

00:05:46.935 --> 00:05:48.810
He used to run around
and make lost of noise.

00:05:48.810 --> 00:05:50.530
Even when he was
pretty calm, he was

00:05:50.530 --> 00:05:53.284
kind of running around, kind
of really stressing out.

00:05:53.284 --> 00:05:54.950
And we'd just be
standing there, cutting

00:05:54.950 --> 00:05:59.390
the vegetables, same
old pace every day.

00:05:59.390 --> 00:06:01.900
And it was amazing.

00:06:01.900 --> 00:06:03.844
He was the only one
running around going,

00:06:03.844 --> 00:06:05.760
it's so noisy in here,
it's so hectic in here.

00:06:05.760 --> 00:06:08.610
And we'd just be, yes, chef.

00:06:08.610 --> 00:06:10.580
And just carry on with
what we were doing.

00:06:10.580 --> 00:06:13.320
And there's a
similar kind of risk,

00:06:13.320 --> 00:06:15.370
you know we read a
lot about mindfulness,

00:06:15.370 --> 00:06:18.810
we talk a lot about it, but
we don't actually do it.

00:06:18.810 --> 00:06:21.810
And there's just one more.

00:06:21.810 --> 00:06:23.397
There's a little
quote from a teacher

00:06:23.397 --> 00:06:24.980
that I remember in
the Tibetan school,

00:06:24.980 --> 00:06:27.210
and he was like,
of all the people,

00:06:27.210 --> 00:06:30.970
of all those who think
about meditation,

00:06:30.970 --> 00:06:33.710
very few people actually begin.

00:06:33.710 --> 00:06:37.360
Of those that begin,
very few continue.

00:06:37.360 --> 00:06:40.464
And of all those that continue,
very few continue to the end,

00:06:40.464 --> 00:06:42.380
whether we see the end
as the end of our life,

00:06:42.380 --> 00:06:46.230
or some kind of
lasting peace of mind.

00:06:46.230 --> 00:06:49.920
And so Headspace has really
grown out of that one quote.

00:06:49.920 --> 00:06:53.200
How do we get people
excited enough to try it?

00:06:53.200 --> 00:06:56.940
When you try it, how can we
keep you engaged in some way?

00:06:56.940 --> 00:07:00.370
And then how can we make
that a lifelong practice?

00:07:00.370 --> 00:07:04.210
So I thought today
we'd look at not just

00:07:04.210 --> 00:07:07.940
mindfulness, but a few
different types of meditation.

00:07:07.940 --> 00:07:10.660
Because for me, that daily
practice-- mindfulness

00:07:10.660 --> 00:07:14.320
is a fantastic way of
introducing meditation

00:07:14.320 --> 00:07:15.550
to the West, I think.

00:07:15.550 --> 00:07:17.420
And the beauty of it,
it translates so well

00:07:17.420 --> 00:07:19.260
into everyday life.

00:07:19.260 --> 00:07:21.780
So you have your daily
routine, your daily practice,

00:07:21.780 --> 00:07:23.020
your daily sit.

00:07:23.020 --> 00:07:26.550
But then you can apply
that to everyday life.

00:07:26.550 --> 00:07:29.890
But it doesn't necessarily
have to be the only way

00:07:29.890 --> 00:07:31.630
to have your daily sit.

00:07:31.630 --> 00:07:34.290
And my own experience-- So
I spent about five years

00:07:34.290 --> 00:07:36.560
training quite strictly in
the Burmese school, which

00:07:36.560 --> 00:07:39.500
is very, very serious.

00:07:39.500 --> 00:07:42.390
And it's all just kind
of straight mindfulness.

00:07:42.390 --> 00:07:45.630
And it was wonderful, and it
was an amazing introduction.

00:07:45.630 --> 00:07:50.340
But for me personally, I still
felt like it hadn't quite

00:07:50.340 --> 00:07:52.460
unlocked all the doors.

00:07:52.460 --> 00:07:54.240
I didn't necessary
find the warmth in it

00:07:54.240 --> 00:07:55.570
that I'd been looking for.

00:07:55.570 --> 00:07:57.486
And I was introduced to
some other techniques,

00:07:57.486 --> 00:07:58.890
and that immediately did it.

00:07:58.890 --> 00:08:01.810
So it's really important to
recognize we're all different,

00:08:01.810 --> 00:08:04.640
and all of us relate to
different types of techniques.

00:08:04.640 --> 00:08:07.480
So I though today,
still very down-to-earth

00:08:07.480 --> 00:08:10.830
stuff, nothing too
wacky, nothing too crazy.

00:08:10.830 --> 00:08:14.870
But just looking at maybe
visualization and reflection

00:08:14.870 --> 00:08:17.780
and just to see how
you get on with those.

00:08:17.780 --> 00:08:19.530
And these are all
things that are included

00:08:19.530 --> 00:08:22.410
as part of Headspace journey,
so this isn't something kind

00:08:22.410 --> 00:08:25.039
of out there or
separate from that.

00:08:25.039 --> 00:08:26.580
BILL DUANE: Yeah,
really look at this

00:08:26.580 --> 00:08:28.800
as trying out
different practices

00:08:28.800 --> 00:08:32.049
in the laboratory of
your own experience.

00:08:32.049 --> 00:08:34.740
We know the research, the
directionality of the research,

00:08:34.740 --> 00:08:35.750
is clear.

00:08:35.750 --> 00:08:39.320
That the more you practice
the more benefit that you get.

00:08:39.320 --> 00:08:41.559
And we know it's really
hard to practice.

00:08:41.559 --> 00:08:43.440
I mean to me, the
dirty little secret

00:08:43.440 --> 00:08:46.690
of mindfulness and
meditation is that it works,

00:08:46.690 --> 00:08:49.750
and most people don't do it.

00:08:49.750 --> 00:08:51.670
Therefore, this group
of people, which

00:08:51.670 --> 00:08:53.420
is not only the
people here at Google

00:08:53.420 --> 00:08:56.950
thinking about mindfulness, but
our partners outside of Google,

00:08:56.950 --> 00:09:00.730
how can we help, how can
we support, how can we

00:09:00.730 --> 00:09:03.700
be of service for you to
find a practice that works

00:09:03.700 --> 00:09:05.910
for you, so you can do
this thing that we know

00:09:05.910 --> 00:09:08.180
will bring benefit for you?

00:09:08.180 --> 00:09:10.010
In this case, for this company?

00:09:10.010 --> 00:09:13.990
And then for the people who
you meet and in the world,

00:09:13.990 --> 00:09:16.850
it all hinges in finding a
practice that works for you

00:09:16.850 --> 00:09:19.340
and that you can
do consistently.

00:09:19.340 --> 00:09:24.370
So my invitation is to
take some joy in the buffet

00:09:24.370 --> 00:09:28.650
you're about to
sample at, and also

00:09:28.650 --> 00:09:30.780
feel OK with how this
experience lands with you.

00:09:30.780 --> 00:09:31.979
This is an investigation.

00:09:31.979 --> 00:09:33.520
ANDY PUDDICOMBE: A
meditation buffet.

00:09:33.520 --> 00:09:35.330
Never heard of it.

00:09:35.330 --> 00:09:36.130
Only at Google.

00:09:38.780 --> 00:09:44.000
The stories of your buffets
are out there everywhere.

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:46.950
What I'd like you
to do is to just,

00:09:46.950 --> 00:09:48.770
and this is for no
particular reason

00:09:48.770 --> 00:09:50.311
other than my own
enjoyment, I'd just

00:09:50.311 --> 00:09:53.410
like you to start with just
patting your head, if you can.

00:09:53.410 --> 00:09:55.480
OK, now you know
where this is going.

00:09:55.480 --> 00:09:59.430
OK, I'd just like you to start
rubbing your stomach, as well.

00:09:59.430 --> 00:10:00.750
All right.

00:10:00.750 --> 00:10:03.490
Now, if you can continue
that, try to keep it nice

00:10:03.490 --> 00:10:05.780
and even, if you
can, patting the head

00:10:05.780 --> 00:10:07.450
and rubbing the stomach.

00:10:07.450 --> 00:10:09.780
Now at the same time,
I'd like you just

00:10:09.780 --> 00:10:12.460
to visualize your
front door at home.

00:10:15.440 --> 00:10:17.980
They start to notice how
everything's-- I'm already

00:10:17.980 --> 00:10:21.010
starting to see a bit of this
going on, as you visualize.

00:10:21.010 --> 00:10:23.630
OK, just come back to
the physical movement

00:10:23.630 --> 00:10:25.970
and then visualize
the front door again.

00:10:25.970 --> 00:10:29.410
Now to add to that, I'd like you
to just very slowly, quietly,

00:10:29.410 --> 00:10:31.742
under your breath, just start
whispering your zip code,

00:10:31.742 --> 00:10:32.450
just to yourself.

00:10:35.267 --> 00:10:37.350
(WHISPERING) Say it a
little bit louder than that.

00:10:42.040 --> 00:10:45.940
OK, and I'll be
back in 90 minutes.

00:10:45.940 --> 00:10:49.220
Now so now how many
of you found yourself

00:10:49.220 --> 00:10:51.040
thinking about, I
don't know, what

00:10:51.040 --> 00:10:52.930
you're doing later in the day?

00:10:52.930 --> 00:10:54.799
No one.

00:10:54.799 --> 00:10:56.340
So something really
interesting here.

00:10:56.340 --> 00:10:58.740
You weren't trying
not to think, you

00:10:58.740 --> 00:11:01.660
were simply directing your mind
with a sense of playfulness,

00:11:01.660 --> 00:11:04.480
kind of interest, curiosity,
whatever you want to call it.

00:11:04.480 --> 00:11:07.570
And actually the mind
was quite focused.

00:11:07.570 --> 00:11:09.480
So the temptation
is, when we sit down

00:11:09.480 --> 00:11:10.980
to meditate first
thing, right, this

00:11:10.980 --> 00:11:12.354
is really kind of
serious, right?

00:11:12.354 --> 00:11:13.730
I need clear my mind.

00:11:13.730 --> 00:11:15.120
Right, focus.

00:11:15.120 --> 00:11:17.220
And of course, the mind
resists against that.

00:11:17.220 --> 00:11:20.340
You then start to
think a lot, usually.

00:11:20.340 --> 00:11:23.960
OK, so if you can bring that
same sense of playfulness

00:11:23.960 --> 00:11:26.630
and ease and lightness
to meditation,

00:11:26.630 --> 00:11:28.730
then it can make
