00:30:23.690 --> 00:30:26.780
Do you want to do one
more question, and then

00:30:26.780 --> 00:30:29.640
we'll do the next exercise?

00:30:29.640 --> 00:30:30.380
Yeah.

00:30:30.380 --> 00:30:34.480
There's a mic just
on its way over.

00:30:34.480 --> 00:30:37.320
ANDY PUDDICOMBE: Got to say,
you're looking man, Andy.

00:30:37.320 --> 00:30:40.530
As one bald guy to another.

00:30:40.530 --> 00:30:44.972
I assume there was no irony
in calling the app Headspace?

00:30:44.972 --> 00:30:45.930
ANDY PUDDICOMBE: Sorry?

00:30:45.930 --> 00:30:47.846
AUDIENCE: I assume there
was no irony involved

00:30:47.846 --> 00:30:49.920
in calling the app Headspace?

00:30:49.920 --> 00:30:53.530
ANDY PUDDICOMBE: No obvious
irony that I'm aware of.

00:30:53.530 --> 00:30:57.710
No, none whatsoever.

00:30:57.710 --> 00:31:01.460
AUDIENCE: Silliness aside,
I've derived tremendous benefit

00:31:01.460 --> 00:31:03.250
for using the app,
and I naturally

00:31:03.250 --> 00:31:05.110
have a fairly
anxious disposition.

00:31:05.110 --> 00:31:07.840
I've fought it all my life.

00:31:07.840 --> 00:31:11.490
My dad has chronic OCD,
and he visited recently.

00:31:11.490 --> 00:31:17.850
And I was like, Dad,
Headspace is dynamite.

00:31:17.850 --> 00:31:19.870
Even if you don't
use Headspace, start

00:31:19.870 --> 00:31:22.120
meditating on a daily basis.

00:31:22.120 --> 00:31:24.440
You are a classic
example of a guy

00:31:24.440 --> 00:31:26.640
who would benefit
greatly from it.

00:31:26.640 --> 00:31:28.390
And he said, I know.

00:31:28.390 --> 00:31:31.330
I said, so Dad, when
are going to do it?

00:31:31.330 --> 00:31:33.310
He said, I'm not going to do it.

00:31:33.310 --> 00:31:34.824
And I said, why not?

00:31:34.824 --> 00:31:36.740
He said, I'm afraid of
what I'm going to find.

00:31:39.820 --> 00:31:42.960
How do I-- I mean, you
can't bring a horse to water

00:31:42.960 --> 00:31:46.950
and make it drink, but do you
have any suggestions for me

00:31:46.950 --> 00:31:50.116
on how I might approach
the conversation.

00:31:50.116 --> 00:31:51.990
ANDY PUDDICOMBE: Yes,
it's a really good one.

00:31:51.990 --> 00:31:55.760
It's definitely a story
I've heard so many times.

00:31:58.290 --> 00:32:01.190
People who know they
would benefit from it,

00:32:01.190 --> 00:32:03.700
but are fearful of
what they might find.

00:32:03.700 --> 00:32:08.050
And often people who aren't even
in that bracket of experiencing

00:32:08.050 --> 00:32:12.740
severe patterns of
thought like OCD.

00:32:12.740 --> 00:32:17.630
My own experience has
been, spending time

00:32:17.630 --> 00:32:19.880
with that individual
and meeting them

00:32:19.880 --> 00:32:23.070
where they are, is the
most important thing.

00:32:23.070 --> 00:32:26.074
So if they're in
one place-- yeah,

00:32:26.074 --> 00:32:27.490
I'm not really
interested in this,

00:32:27.490 --> 00:32:29.640
and we're in the other place,
you should really do this,

00:32:29.640 --> 00:32:31.473
you should really do
this-- there inevitably

00:32:31.473 --> 00:32:33.990
is going to be some tension.

00:32:33.990 --> 00:32:35.940
For me it's like a dance.

00:32:35.940 --> 00:32:37.550
You go with them.

00:32:37.550 --> 00:32:39.090
Where are they going with it?

00:32:39.090 --> 00:32:40.484
OK, why don't they
want to do it?

00:32:40.484 --> 00:32:42.900
So you go with them, and you
go down that story with them,

00:32:42.900 --> 00:32:44.740
and you listen to them
and hear them out.

00:32:44.740 --> 00:32:47.640
And what I found very
useful is getting

00:32:47.640 --> 00:32:49.980
them to not do meditation.

00:32:49.980 --> 00:32:52.150
Get them to say
quietly for 10 seconds.

00:32:52.150 --> 00:32:53.780
And see what happens.

00:32:53.780 --> 00:32:56.330
And after 10 seconds,
based on experience,

00:32:56.330 --> 00:32:58.430
was that terrifying?

00:32:58.430 --> 00:33:01.490
And often, 10 seconds
feels kind of manageable.

00:33:01.490 --> 00:33:04.040
Doesn't feel too scary,
doesn't feel too threatening.

00:33:04.040 --> 00:33:05.860
OK what does 20
seconds feel like?

00:33:05.860 --> 00:33:07.640
What does 30 seconds feel like?

00:33:07.640 --> 00:33:10.910
I do think with some people
it's about building it up.

00:33:10.910 --> 00:33:13.400
And always it's
about experience.

00:33:13.400 --> 00:33:16.400
So if you go right back to the
very beginning of the tradition

00:33:16.400 --> 00:33:19.360
of these teachings,
it's like try it.

00:33:19.360 --> 00:33:23.420
If it works for
you, then try this.

00:33:23.420 --> 00:33:24.020
Try that.

00:33:24.020 --> 00:33:25.190
If that works, you try this.

00:33:25.190 --> 00:33:28.670
So what is the smallest
unit we can get someone

00:33:28.670 --> 00:33:32.210
to engage with to experience
that sense of trust

00:33:32.210 --> 00:33:36.000
and confidence, so they can
then go on and try the next bit?

00:33:36.000 --> 00:33:38.320
And it is always unique
to every person, at least

00:33:38.320 --> 00:33:39.680
that's my own experience.

00:33:39.680 --> 00:33:43.150
And we can put out an
app like Headspace,

00:33:43.150 --> 00:33:46.440
but it is quite
generic by nature.

00:33:46.440 --> 00:33:50.200
And so in situations like that,
definitely having a family

00:33:50.200 --> 00:33:54.000
member or friend who can
help shape it a little bit,

00:33:54.000 --> 00:33:55.620
and help them
experiment with it I

00:33:55.620 --> 00:33:57.560
think is a really useful thing.

00:33:57.560 --> 00:33:58.481
I don't know.

00:33:58.481 --> 00:33:59.980
BILL DUANE: Yeah,
I agree with that.

00:33:59.980 --> 00:34:01.990
And I think if
someone doesn't want

00:34:01.990 --> 00:34:04.030
to meditate, that's
completely fine.

00:34:04.030 --> 00:34:04.957
That was me.

00:34:04.957 --> 00:34:07.290
People were just like, you
should really try meditation.

00:34:07.290 --> 00:34:09.560
I'd just be like,
forget you, hippy.

00:34:09.560 --> 00:34:10.330
Right?

00:34:10.330 --> 00:34:12.194
It's clearly in
the same box as--

00:34:12.194 --> 00:34:13.610
and I apologize
if there's anybody

00:34:13.610 --> 00:34:15.790
who's into this-- like
crystals, and auras.

00:34:15.790 --> 00:34:17.564
And I'm a scientist.

00:34:17.564 --> 00:34:18.230
I'm an engineer.

00:34:18.230 --> 00:34:19.951
That's not for me.

00:34:19.951 --> 00:34:21.659
And it wasn't until
I went to a tech talk

00:34:21.659 --> 00:34:25.250
on the neuroscience of
emotion, and my own discomfort

00:34:25.250 --> 00:34:27.429
and suffering was great
enough where I'm like,

00:34:27.429 --> 00:34:30.110
OK, maybe this is for me.

00:34:30.110 --> 00:34:33.159
And I think if someone had tried
to force it on me before then,

00:34:33.159 --> 00:34:35.960
it would have actually
driven me farther away.

00:34:35.960 --> 00:34:38.060
So I think that
saying, not for me,

00:34:38.060 --> 00:34:41.429
is a perfectly
acceptable answer.

00:34:41.429 --> 00:34:43.610
This is difficult.

00:34:43.610 --> 00:34:47.580
This is joyful and rewarding
work, but it's also difficult.

00:34:47.580 --> 00:34:49.850
And I think it's
important for people

00:34:49.850 --> 00:34:54.000
to make an informed choice
to engage with this practice.

00:34:54.000 --> 00:34:55.120
Realizing it's hard.

00:34:55.120 --> 00:34:58.950
So I think just saying, not
for them right now, is fine.

00:34:58.950 --> 00:35:03.780
And I firmly believe that
a big part of practice

00:35:03.780 --> 00:35:07.670
is for the benefit of the people
who have to deal with you.

00:35:07.670 --> 00:35:13.260
And I know that a lot of times
the changes in how I show up

00:35:13.260 --> 00:35:16.510
and how I am in the world, a lot
of times people will be like,

00:35:16.510 --> 00:35:17.710
what happened?

00:35:17.710 --> 00:35:20.585
A little disturbed that it's--
What was it like before?

00:35:25.090 --> 00:35:27.530
And really they're saying, wow.

00:35:27.530 --> 00:35:31.260
It's not like reading about the
neuroscience, it was just like,

00:35:31.260 --> 00:35:35.690
man, I really noticed you
just seem a lot happier, more

00:35:35.690 --> 00:35:37.420
effective, the parts
of your personality

00:35:37.420 --> 00:35:40.380
that most annoy
me are less there.

00:35:40.380 --> 00:35:43.690
So working on yourself,
and showing up

00:35:43.690 --> 00:35:49.270
in the world as focused, as
compassionate, as generous,

00:35:49.270 --> 00:35:50.350
and as a good listener.

00:35:50.350 --> 00:35:52.870
These are all the things that
come out of this practice.

00:35:52.870 --> 00:35:54.620
Just work on that,
and then that's

00:35:54.620 --> 00:35:57.550
the best billboard
for it, I find.

00:36:01.210 --> 00:36:04.270
ANDY PUDDICOMBE: So shall
we do another exercise?

00:36:04.270 --> 00:36:08.470
How many of you have done
virtualization before?

00:36:08.470 --> 00:36:09.935
Any kind of visualization?

00:36:09.935 --> 00:36:11.230
OK, not so many.

00:36:11.230 --> 00:36:18.620
OK, so I'm going to try to theme
the exercises today so they all

00:36:18.620 --> 00:36:22.130
have a link between all of them.

00:36:22.130 --> 00:36:24.650
The visualization we're
going to do right now

00:36:24.650 --> 00:36:28.346
is still kind of body
based, if you like.

00:36:28.346 --> 00:36:29.970
And there's a benefit
to that, and I'll

00:36:29.970 --> 00:36:32.700
explain why afterwards.

00:36:32.700 --> 00:36:35.340
I'm going to ask you
during the visualization

00:36:35.340 --> 00:36:36.990
to imagine sunlight.

00:36:36.990 --> 00:36:40.790
Now this is really important.

00:36:40.790 --> 00:36:44.790
You can see there's nothing
weird or wacky about sunlight.

00:36:44.790 --> 00:36:47.820
Imagine bright sunlight,
streaming through the trees,

00:36:47.820 --> 00:36:49.390
or whatever it might be.

00:36:49.390 --> 00:36:53.120
So if I talk about light
during the exercise,

00:36:53.120 --> 00:36:55.540
I'm not talking about a
bright white light or anything

00:36:55.540 --> 00:36:56.340
like that.

00:36:56.340 --> 00:36:59.150
I'm just talking about sunlight,
just the quality of sunlight.

00:36:59.150 --> 00:37:01.410
It's warm, it's
open, it's spacious.

00:37:01.410 --> 00:37:04.470
There's something kind
of really useful in that.

00:37:04.470 --> 00:37:06.920
BILL DUANE: Any unicorns
in the visualization?

00:37:06.920 --> 00:37:09.110
Is the light coming
from the unicorn?

00:37:09.110 --> 00:37:11.318
ANDY PUDDICOMBE: I think
