ANDY PUDDICOMBE:
OK, there's actually

01:02:14.240 --> 01:02:16.940
some great tips in Take 20,
but that's a terrible thing

01:02:16.940 --> 01:02:19.480
to suggest.

01:02:19.480 --> 01:02:24.980
As soon as you said it,
well that's what Take 20 is.

01:02:24.980 --> 01:02:28.930
It's all about settling into
discomfort, and how approach it

01:02:28.930 --> 01:02:29.930
and how to deal with it.

01:02:29.930 --> 01:02:33.700
But don't worry, I'm not
going to suggest that.

01:02:33.700 --> 01:02:36.870
Does as the pain
continue after you get up

01:02:36.870 --> 01:02:38.495
and you finish you meditation?

01:02:38.495 --> 01:02:40.120
OK, so that's a really
important point.

01:02:40.120 --> 01:02:42.870
So if it does, then there maybe
something about your sitting,

01:02:42.870 --> 01:02:45.270
or there maybe something a
bit more structural there,

01:02:45.270 --> 01:02:47.570
and you might want
to get that seen to,

01:02:47.570 --> 01:02:49.230
or speak to someone about it.

01:02:49.230 --> 01:02:51.850
If it doesn't, there are certain
kind of pains and discomfort

01:02:51.850 --> 01:02:54.152
which arise during meditation.

01:02:54.152 --> 01:02:55.860
And if you're really
cautious about this,

01:02:55.860 --> 01:02:58.160
and if you are at all
concerned, of course

01:02:58.160 --> 01:02:59.800
you need to see your doctor.

01:02:59.800 --> 01:03:00.920
It's really important.

01:03:00.920 --> 01:03:03.004
But my only experience
has been, and I

01:03:03.004 --> 01:03:05.690
know the experience of many
friends is, when we sit,

01:03:05.690 --> 01:03:07.960
sometimes we
experience discomfort.

01:03:07.960 --> 01:03:11.030
And there can be a
temptation or tendency

01:03:11.030 --> 01:03:13.880
to really want to move
away from that discomfort.

01:03:13.880 --> 01:03:16.190
It's like we just
can't bear it anymore.

01:03:16.190 --> 01:03:18.250
But as long as
it's not pain which

01:03:18.250 --> 01:03:20.030
is causing us
further discomfort,

01:03:20.030 --> 01:03:23.630
there is some benefit
sometimes to sitting with that,

01:03:23.630 --> 01:03:25.340
and being interested in it.

01:03:25.340 --> 01:03:27.580
Again, it's a bit like
the boredom thing.

01:03:27.580 --> 01:03:32.000
Can we step back from it
enough to step out of that loop

01:03:32.000 --> 01:03:35.014
where it hurts, physically,
and therefore our mind is

01:03:35.014 --> 01:03:36.180
like, oh, that really hurts.

01:03:36.180 --> 01:03:37.920
And therefore it gets
a bit more tense.

01:03:37.920 --> 01:03:39.660
And then the mind goes,
oh, now it really hurts,

01:03:39.660 --> 01:03:41.118
I've got to stop,
I've got to stop.

01:03:41.118 --> 01:03:43.730
OK, if we can step out
of that circle and go,

01:03:43.730 --> 01:03:45.560
OK, that's interesting.

01:03:48.210 --> 01:03:49.780
What is that?

01:03:49.780 --> 01:03:51.980
How does that feel?

01:03:51.980 --> 01:03:53.130
What is the discomfort?

01:03:53.130 --> 01:03:58.410
Is the discomfort either a heavy
dull feeling, is it a sharp,

01:03:58.410 --> 01:03:59.920
stabbing feeling?

01:03:59.920 --> 01:04:03.870
Start to be more interested
in the feeling itself.

01:04:03.870 --> 01:04:06.720
And very often when we
do that, the feeling

01:04:06.720 --> 01:04:11.100
starts to change and shift,
and our relationship to it

01:04:11.100 --> 01:04:12.710
changes, as well.

01:04:12.710 --> 01:04:16.480
So you might just want to have
a play with that, and just see.

01:04:16.480 --> 01:04:19.720
But if not, send
us in an e-mail,

01:04:19.720 --> 01:04:22.577
put it as a title
heading, Andy's Answers.

01:04:22.577 --> 01:04:24.410
And we've got a little
section, because that

01:04:24.410 --> 01:04:26.480
would make a really nice
blog thing, as well.

01:04:26.480 --> 01:04:29.179
So happy to add
some more to that.

01:04:29.179 --> 01:04:30.720
BILL DUANE: And it's
always a balance

01:04:30.720 --> 01:04:33.680
between engaging with
the difficult to be

01:04:33.680 --> 01:04:37.030
curious about it, and self care.

01:04:37.030 --> 01:04:39.690
I really believe
everything that Andy said,

01:04:39.690 --> 01:04:41.590
and I really had some
interesting experiences

01:04:41.590 --> 01:04:44.120
with instead of doing the
automatic thing, which is ow,

01:04:44.120 --> 01:04:45.090
stop it.

01:04:45.090 --> 01:04:47.640
More like, what's my
relationship to ow?

01:04:47.640 --> 01:04:49.960
And then you actually build
up a much greater sense

01:04:49.960 --> 01:04:53.470
of possible responses, other
than make it stop right now.

01:04:53.470 --> 01:04:55.620
But sometimes we don't
have that available to us.

01:04:55.620 --> 01:04:59.580
And it's important not to
turn this into an iron man.

01:04:59.580 --> 01:05:05.070
Like grrrrr, oh, I hurt
so much, this is-- No.

01:05:05.070 --> 01:05:08.670
We started off with saying that
meditation provides benefit,

01:05:08.670 --> 01:05:10.190
and a lot of people don't do it.

01:05:10.190 --> 01:05:11.960
And if you set up
a situation where

01:05:11.960 --> 01:05:14.314
it's so unpleasant
for you-- So I

01:05:14.314 --> 01:05:16.480
would say that it's important
to challenge yourself,

01:05:16.480 --> 01:05:20.250
but also to have a sense of
balance of the challenge.

01:05:20.250 --> 01:05:23.210
If you find yourself not
wanting to sit because it's

01:05:23.210 --> 01:05:25.990
going to be painful, you're
probably veering more

01:05:25.990 --> 01:05:27.990
towards the overly
challenge. side.

01:05:27.990 --> 01:05:29.323
ANDY PUDDICOMBE: I would say so.

01:05:29.323 --> 01:05:31.570
And just as on
from that as well,

01:05:31.570 --> 01:05:33.630
I personally, I don't
have a problem--

01:05:33.630 --> 01:05:35.460
I know some meditation
teachers who

01:05:35.460 --> 01:05:38.562
don't like the idea of lying
down or anything like that.

01:05:38.562 --> 01:05:40.020
Meditation was
taught traditionally

01:05:40.020 --> 01:05:41.980
in four different
postures, and one of them

01:05:41.980 --> 01:05:44.850
was lying, actually.

01:05:44.850 --> 01:05:48.290
If you do lie, try and do
it in a way that you're not

01:05:48.290 --> 01:05:50.060
setting yourself up
for sleep, because it

01:05:50.060 --> 01:05:52.190
is very easy to
drift towards sleep.

01:05:52.190 --> 01:05:55.720
So lie on a soft mat,
but on a firm surface.

01:05:55.720 --> 01:05:58.164
Have the knees
bent at 90 degrees,

01:05:58.164 --> 01:05:59.580
so you don't hurt
your lower back.

01:05:59.580 --> 01:06:00.560
Feet flat on the floor.

01:06:00.560 --> 01:06:03.120
And a very thin pillow
under your head.

01:06:03.120 --> 01:06:04.370
And see how you go, as well.

01:06:04.370 --> 01:06:09.240
So I think you can be confident
in experimenting, a little bit.

01:06:09.240 --> 01:06:12.305
BILL DUANE: And even on long,
multi-day silent retreats,

01:06:12.305 --> 01:06:13.680
there will always
be a few people

01:06:13.680 --> 01:06:16.110
for whom that's their posture.

01:06:16.110 --> 01:06:17.240
And that's totally fine.

01:06:20.164 --> 01:06:21.080
ANDY PUDDICOMBE: Cool.

01:06:21.080 --> 01:06:22.705
I know there's a
couple more questions.

01:06:22.705 --> 01:06:24.745
Have we got time for
one more quick exercise?

01:06:24.745 --> 01:06:26.620
BILL DUANE: Why don't
we do a quick exercise,

01:06:26.620 --> 01:06:28.620
and then also we have
the Dory questions.

01:06:28.620 --> 01:06:30.536
I want to make sure
particularly for the folks

01:06:30.536 --> 01:06:32.397
on video conference,
and for the folks here.

01:06:32.397 --> 01:06:34.730
Let's do an exercise, then
we'll do some more questions.

01:06:34.730 --> 01:06:36.271
ANDY PUDDICOMBE:
OK, we're just going

01:06:36.271 --> 01:06:39.010
to do a really quick,
not really quick.

01:06:39.010 --> 01:06:41.950
Not a hurried meditation.

01:06:41.950 --> 01:06:43.850
We're going to do
a short excise.

01:06:43.850 --> 01:06:45.390
It's reflection.

01:06:45.390 --> 01:06:48.930
Anyone done this type
of exercise before?

01:06:48.930 --> 01:06:51.640
It's where you're
asking a question,

01:06:51.640 --> 01:06:54.830
but you're not
trying to answer it.

01:06:54.830 --> 01:06:57.950
Which is a challenge
for most people.

01:06:57.950 --> 01:06:59.940
But it's a really
interesting challenge.

01:06:59.940 --> 01:07:02.860
And it's quite an exciting
space to get into, just

01:07:02.860 --> 01:07:04.190
generally in life.

01:07:04.190 --> 01:07:06.880
Not always trying to use the
rational intellectual mind

01:07:06.880 --> 01:07:09.680
to try and answer stuff.

01:07:09.680 --> 01:07:12.540
So it's an excise I've
found really helpful.

01:07:12.540 --> 01:07:14.020
It was described
to me a bit like,

01:07:14.020 --> 01:07:17.570
we help create the
conditions, a framework,

01:07:17.570 --> 01:07:18.690
for a still pool of water.

01:07:18.690 --> 01:07:21.242
And then we just
drop the question,

01:07:21.242 --> 01:07:23.980
and we just sit back and watch.

01:07:23.980 --> 01:07:27.120
Maybe something pops
up, maybe it doesn't.

01:07:27.120 --> 01:07:28.550
No answer is OK.

01:07:28.550 --> 01:07:30.420
We're not necessarily
looking for an answer,

01:07:30.420 --> 01:07:33.090
we're just watching
to see what happens.

01:07:33.090 --> 01:07:34.800
Sometimes it will
come as a feeling,

01:07:34.800 --> 01:07:36.940
sometimes it will
come as a thought.

01:07:36.940 --> 01:07:37.690
It's OK.

01:07:37.690 --> 01:07:39.570
I'll talk you
through the exercise.

01:07:39.570 --> 01:07:42.364
But there's just one
little bit about this.

01:07:42.364 --> 01:07:44.030
And because the
intellectual mind always

01:07:44.030 --> 01:07:46.441
wants to take over
the whole time,

01:07:46.441 --> 01:07:47.690
it's a really important thing.

01:07:47.690 --> 01:07:49.980
There's a guy that
came along to-- I

01:07:49.980 --> 01:07:53.110
used to work at a
clinic in London--

01:07:53.110 --> 01:07:56.070
and we were doing this exercise.

01:07:56.070 --> 01:08:00.760
And I said, OK, I can't remember
what the question was exactly,

01:08:00.760 --> 01:08:04.970
it was something to the effect
of, what would you miss most

01:08:04.970 --> 01:08:08.400
if you weren't around anymore?

01:08:08.400 --> 01:08:10.590
Now we did the
exercise together.

01:08:10.590 --> 01:08:14.010
And afterwards, I
said OK, how was it?

01:08:14.010 --> 01:08:15.020
And he told me.

01:08:15.020 --> 01:08:18.477
And he said, but I feel
really a bit uncomfortable.

01:08:18.477 --> 01:08:19.560
Do you mind if I tell you?

01:08:19.560 --> 01:08:21.460
I said, well you don't have
to tell me what it was.

01:08:21.460 --> 01:08:23.600
And he said, no, I want
to tell you what it was.

01:08:23.600 --> 01:08:26.279
He said, look, you know
I have an amazing wife,

01:08:26.279 --> 01:08:29.870
I have amazing kids,
I've got a brilliant job,

01:08:29.870 --> 01:08:31.080
I've got my business.

01:08:31.080 --> 01:08:33.140
My life's incredible.

01:08:33.140 --> 01:08:37.399
He said but, honestly the
thing that about the feeling

01:08:37.399 --> 01:08:41.492
of what I'd miss most, is
my morning cup of coffee.

01:08:41.492 --> 01:08:43.700
And so he said, I really
kind of struggled with this.

01:08:43.700 --> 01:08:48.040
I spent most of the rest of the
meditation thinking, oh, shoot.

01:08:48.040 --> 01:08:49.653
My wife?

01:08:49.653 --> 01:08:51.040
My kids?

01:08:51.040 --> 01:08:52.560
Really?

01:08:52.560 --> 01:08:55.670
So he felt really
guilty about it.

01:08:55.670 --> 01:08:58.140
There are no judgments
on what comes up.

01:08:58.140 --> 01:08:59.568
There is no right or wrong.

01:08:59.568 --> 01:09:01.109
And actually when
we talked about it,

01:09:01.109 --> 01:09:02.984
it was really interesting
because his morning

01:09:02.984 --> 01:09:05.450
cup of coffee was his moment.

01:09:05.450 --> 01:09:09.460
His wife was still in bed
asleep, he got up very early.

01:09:09.460 --> 01:09:12.510
He didn't have to communicate,
talk with anybody.

01:09:12.510 --> 01:09:14.120
The kids were still sleeping.

01:09:14.120 --> 01:09:16.109
He hadn't yet got
in to his work.

01:09:16.109 --> 01:09:19.300
And he had those 10
minutes on his own

01:09:19.300 --> 01:09:22.060
where he would just smell
the coffee, taste it.

01:09:22.060 --> 01:09:25.060
It was kind of like a little
mini mindfulness thing.

01:09:25.060 --> 01:09:26.870
He didn't even know
he was doing it.

01:09:26.870 --> 01:09:30.160
And yet, it was
that feeling-- when

01:09:30.160 --> 01:09:33.319
he asked that question--
it was that feeling which

01:09:33.319 --> 01:09:35.229
had arisen in him.

01:09:35.229 --> 01:09:37.029
And that's what
gave the feeling.

01:09:37.029 --> 01:09:39.180
This is more about
feeling than thought.

01:09:39.180 --> 01:09:41.490
So don't think that
has to be like a,

01:09:41.490 --> 01:09:43.720
oh yes, I would miss
my mother-in-law.

01:09:43.720 --> 01:09:45.250
Or whatever it is.

01:09:45.250 --> 01:09:45.870
OK?

01:09:45.870 --> 01:09:48.010
It doesn't have to
be like that, OK?

01:09:48.010 --> 01:09:50.420
It can just be
perhaps a feeling.

01:09:50.420 --> 01:09:53.779
So we'll lean in that direction.

01:09:53.779 --> 01:09:55.570
We're going to set up
in just the same way,

01:09:55.570 --> 01:09:57.440
so take a moment
to get comfortable.

01:10:03.120 --> 01:10:05.190
If you've already done
a couple of-- I normally

01:10:05.190 --> 01:10:08.122
spend a little bit longer
on the set-up to this.

01:10:08.122 --> 01:10:10.080
I know I'm conscious we
don't have lots of time

01:10:10.080 --> 01:10:12.310
as we've just done a
couple of exercises.

01:10:12.310 --> 01:10:14.980
We'll just move
through it steadily.

01:10:14.980 --> 01:10:18.776
But you already know the
beginning part of this,

01:10:18.776 --> 01:10:21.400
of course, which is just
getting yourself comfortable,

01:10:21.400 --> 01:10:24.140
eyes open, nice soft gaze.

01:10:24.140 --> 01:10:26.610
And just taking just
two or three nice big,

01:10:26.610 --> 01:10:29.910
deep breaths where you
breathe in through the nose,

01:10:29.910 --> 01:10:31.020
and out through the mouth.

01:10:40.550 --> 01:10:45.160
And on the next exhalation,
just gently closing the eyes.

01:10:49.510 --> 01:10:53.460
You're already conscious,
aware, in touch

01:10:53.460 --> 01:10:58.950
with those feelings of the
body on the chair, feet

01:10:58.950 --> 01:11:02.855
on the floor, hands on the legs.

01:11:11.310 --> 01:11:13.150
We're already starting
to notice the sounds.

01:11:27.126 --> 01:11:28.875
Now as you just turn
the attention inwards

01:11:28.875 --> 01:11:31.770
and begin to scan once more.

01:11:31.770 --> 01:11:36.170
Just take 20, 30 seconds just
scanning down through the body.

01:11:36.170 --> 01:11:38.410
Maybe it feels the
same as before,

01:11:38.410 --> 01:11:41.130
perhaps different this time.

01:11:41.130 --> 01:11:42.950
Just scanning down
towards the toes.

01:12:17.830 --> 01:12:19.760
As you scan downwards,
just starting

01:12:19.760 --> 01:12:26.340
to become more aware of the
breath and that movement

01:12:26.340 --> 01:12:29.720
of the breath again.

01:12:29.720 --> 01:12:32.102
Just pausing to notice the
breath, if only for 20,

01:12:32.102 --> 01:12:33.875
30 seconds.

01:13:05.880 --> 01:13:08.700
Now just settling
the mind in that way.

01:13:15.410 --> 01:13:19.220
And I'd just like you to
ask yourself that question.

01:13:19.220 --> 01:13:22.920
The one we just used,
in the second person.

01:13:22.920 --> 01:13:29.650
Now who or what would
you miss the most

01:13:29.650 --> 01:13:31.220
if you were no longer around?

01:13:38.466 --> 01:13:40.090
And we just put the
question out there.

01:13:43.790 --> 01:13:48.120
Perhaps something
immediately comes to mind.

01:13:48.120 --> 01:13:51.180
If they're thoughts, just
let the thoughts bubble up,

01:13:51.180 --> 01:13:53.190
that's fine.

01:13:53.190 --> 01:13:59.150
If it's a feeling that arises,
we just sit with that feeling.

01:14:03.854 --> 01:14:05.770
Feel present with that
movement of the breath.

01:14:17.400 --> 01:14:19.300
If nothing comes up,
that's fine, too.

01:14:19.300 --> 01:14:25.274
We can just come back to the
breath again for a moment,

01:14:25.274 --> 01:14:26.440
staying with that sensation.

01:14:40.110 --> 01:14:43.140
And then if no particular
feeling arose the first time

01:14:43.140 --> 01:14:46.180
around, without
forcing it, just gently

01:14:46.180 --> 01:14:50.470
asking that same question again.

01:14:50.470 --> 01:14:56.717
Who or what would
you miss the most

01:14:56.717 --> 01:14:57.925
if you were no longer around?

01:15:13.240 --> 01:15:20.870
And this exercise is about
the feeling, rather than

01:15:20.870 --> 01:15:22.700
any particular idea or thought.

01:15:51.100 --> 01:15:53.920
It's almost as though
we're watching the breath,

01:15:53.920 --> 01:15:58.740
but the breath is flavored
with a particular feeling.

01:15:58.740 --> 01:16:03.840
And we just stay with that,
not wanting the failing

01:16:03.840 --> 01:16:06.325
to continue, not wanting to end.

01:16:06.325 --> 01:16:14.830
But just watching it as
It arises and falls away.

01:16:17.500 --> 01:16:20.120
And if there's no feeling
whatsoever, that's OK, too.

01:16:20.120 --> 01:16:21.430
Just staying with the breath.

01:16:53.120 --> 01:16:55.250
And then typically
in these exercises,

01:16:55.250 --> 01:16:58.550
we work through a number
of different questions.

01:16:58.550 --> 01:17:02.050
But for today, I'd just like you
to gently bring your attention

01:17:02.050 --> 01:17:04.840
back once again.

01:17:04.840 --> 01:17:09.870
The body to the
physical sensations,

01:17:09.870 --> 01:17:15.610
back to that feeling
of weight on the chair,

01:17:15.610 --> 01:17:18.795
feet on the floor,
hands on the legs.

01:17:22.920 --> 01:17:26.800
And in your own time,
when you're ready,

01:17:26.800 --> 01:17:29.150
you can just gently
open your eyes again.

01:17:36.370 --> 01:17:38.940
It's always a
tricky balance when

01:17:38.940 --> 01:17:40.900
you want to do a
meditation excise,

01:17:40.900 --> 01:17:44.100
but there's not a lot of time.

01:17:44.100 --> 01:17:46.530
Didn't want to try and
squeeze too much in there,

01:17:46.530 --> 01:17:49.280
but hopefully enough
to give you a flavor.

01:17:49.280 --> 01:17:52.079
So typically there are
four, in an exercise

01:17:52.079 --> 01:17:53.620
like that, there'd
be four questions.

01:17:53.620 --> 01:17:56.150
And we'd work through
one after another.

01:17:56.150 --> 01:17:58.210
If you do more of
the Headspace packs,

01:17:58.210 --> 01:18:00.750
you'll come across that
exercise quite a lot.

01:18:00.750 --> 01:18:04.340
It's used a lot within the
Tibetan tradition I trained in.

01:18:04.340 --> 01:18:07.270
And it's really interesting.

01:18:07.270 --> 01:18:10.150
One letting go is, I
say, is that ability

01:18:10.150 --> 01:18:12.470
to-- of that instinct,
that impulse,

01:18:12.470 --> 01:18:15.610
to always try and
rationally work it out.

01:18:15.610 --> 01:18:18.650
Instead getting in touch
with feeling and instinct

01:18:18.650 --> 01:18:19.970
and intuition.

01:18:19.970 --> 01:18:23.040
Really, really
valuable for that.

01:18:23.040 --> 01:18:25.290
But the kind of
questions that arise,

01:18:25.290 --> 01:18:31.930
or the feeling that arises,
is often very surprising.

01:18:31.930 --> 01:18:33.730
In my own experience,
and the feedback

01:18:33.730 --> 01:18:36.279
from people that use it, is
that they're often taken aback,

01:18:36.279 --> 01:18:38.070
and they never even
knew they felt that way

01:18:38.070 --> 01:18:40.120
about the question being asked.

01:18:40.120 --> 01:18:43.700
So something to have a look at.

01:18:43.700 --> 01:18:47.180
But Bill, I know you wanted
to go through some questions

01:18:47.180 --> 01:18:50.140
before we wrap things up.

01:18:50.140 --> 01:18:52.620
BILL DUANE: Yeah, just a
